Lilybelle Snugglebunny <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=raxtullmortissaurus>Raxtull Mortissaurus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/22/03 4:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2032.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Military</span><hr size=1> I say if he absolutely must join the services, then he should go Air Force.  It's the only service that treats its people as more than just another piece of equipment.  I made the mistake of joining the Navy and there's a huge difference between the Hickam Air Force Base next door and Pearl Harbor where I'm at.  Hickam's uptown, and PH is the ghetto.  Whereas the Army and Marine Corps bases here are more like suburbia near the ghetto. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=strydin9>Strydin9</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Quiet Ranger of the Falls</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/22/03 7:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2032.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Military</span><hr size=1> I would ask your brother what his future plans include before he decides.  <br>
     If he is going in for college money, education, or a short tour then air force is the choice.  They have the best housing, facilities, and allow their members a better chance to improve thier education while gaining valued skills for civilian life.<br>
     The army is not an easy enviroment.  It is harsh at times, things can become very unpredictable fast and with constent deployments army schools and college courses arent easy to get except thru correspodence courses and online classes.         <br>
     Now I will always be on the side of the army as I spent 8 years active, most of it in germany, as mechanized infantry dismount and then medic..  I did three long deployments that at the time I silently complained to myself about but would never want to lose the memeries of.  While the air force teaches you how to manage men the army teaches you how to lead from the front.  While the air force usually sleeps in bays or at least tents, in the army you might find yourself curled under a tree with just a poncho to try to keep dry.  (never works)  Most gear the air force uses isnt on thier back like an army soldier who at times may carry well over 100 pounds in gear.  Add an objective 15 miles away and it becomes an interesting mission.<br>
     Now I am sure there are MOSs in the army that allow more time for soldiers to get an education but as infantry their is very little.  But I dont know your brothers choice of job either.    I left with only the education I got by taking any class when it became available and my medical training.  But I learned other valued skills much harder to get in the civilain world.  And as any military person can tell you once you go military you will never be able to look at a civilain in the same way.  It changes you.<br>
<br>
The one thing I would recommend to your brother is to review in detail the occupations he is interested in and then decide where he wants to go.  But no matter what job he chooses he will only perform that job 50 percent of the time.  there is always a nice list of duties the recruiter fails to tell you.  How many here remember hearing about dry sweap from their recruiter.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rollin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/roll.gif ALT=":rollin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tudilfv>TudilFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/22/03 7:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2032.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Military</span><hr size=1> 2 years active Army and 20 years ARNG. My own father recruited, me, my two brothers, and my sister. I was the only one who stuck it out 'till retirement. That said...Go Air Force!<br>
It's the only branch of the sevice that send the officers out to fight while the enlisted stay back where it's safe, and warm, and dry, and you can go to school. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rollin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/roll.gif ALT=":rollin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I tried to go to school in the Army, but field training exercises kept interfering with my classes. <br>
<br>
No matter what cushy MOS you think you're getting in the Army, the Army will find a way to screw it up. I went to see an active duty recruiter (father was a Nat'l Guard recruiter). I'm color blind so that limited anything in the electronics, medical, or combat fields. I hated typing in highschool so I knew I didn't want that. The recruiter told me my MOS would be a 31C single channel radio operator. Yeah, right. It's also known as a radio teletype operator...key word there is type.<br>
I spent 10 weeks in the middle of the hottest, muggiest weather I ever endured, in Augusta GA. Nasty place. <br>
<br>
I was stationed at FT Bliss and assigned to a Patriot missile battery that had no equipment at all. None, zero, zilch, which is why I started attending classes at UTEP. 4 weeks later the new stuff started rolling in. All brand new, in crates or boxes. The vehicles had less than 30 miles on them in most cases. So, being a radio teletype operator, I was assigned to be the battery commander's driver. For two years, I drove her, and then him around. Spent every freakin' week in the field testing this stuff. In the mid 80's the Patriot system was still experimental. So after all the time and money the army spent training me to be a radio teletype operator, I never ever once saw the inside or a RATT rig. I became a...truck driver, LOL<br>
And that was scoring a 94 on my AASVAB test. Only needed a 30 to pass.<br>
<br>
so yeah, GO AIR FORCE <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=bloops>Bloops</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/22/03 8:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2032.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Military</span><hr size=1> If he whats to join the service, Why no go all out and be a Marine.  I am not going to lie(because I am not a recruiter). The Marines is a tough life but fair worth the respect you get being in it.  Plus you will get great job offers when you get out.  Join The air force if you are Lazy.  The army just sucks.  They treat you like shit and none of the other services like you.  Same with the community.  Join the navy if you can't make it through Marine Corps Boot camp and what to hang around Marines.  But in all of them you get good benefits and A chance to go to school..college for free.  All up to your brother were he goes.  But if he is lazy make sure he does not join the Marines..He will Hate Life.<br>
