<br>
Now, with that out of the way.  I'd say it all depends on what your brother wants out of his time in the service.  Is he planning on becoming a career military man?  or is he interested in a tour or two and then taking advantage of the benefits? (college, etc).<br>
<br>
Either way, I (and my brother looking over my shoulder) cant recommend enough, that he pursue a M.O.S. (job) that will benefit him when he gets out.  The military offers alot of trade and technical training that anyone should take advantage of, and much of that can earn him any number of nice job opportunities as a civilian.  There isn't much call in civilian life for paratroopers, but if he looks into some of the nuclear fields the navy offers, he could very well land a pricey job when he's ready to become a civilian once again.<br>
<br>
Whichever branch he chooses, DO NOT let him fall for the bravado the Army/Marine Corps spouts off about.  While there is alot of tradition in both branches, neither of them are today, what they were in world war 1 and 2 (and the days of Chesty Puller and other &quot;famous&quot; soldiers)... in the sense that going to Parris Island, or San Diego for 12 weeks or training or so will instantly allow you to whip 5 men.<br>
<br>
The best bet would be to look into all branches.. find out what they offer, and then set down with the family and discuss the long term goals and effects of a service term.  We are in an age where it seems that we fall into one war after another, so long deployments into unfriendly areas seem very likely.  Even today soldiers are being wounded or killed in Iraq, and who knows where tomorrows war will be fought...<br>
<br>
Talk with your family, friends.. know that there are risks that dont end with yourself, since soldiers in war zones have worried families at home.  I have a brother who was a planned &quot;lifer&quot; in the Marine Corps, who was wounded in Iraq; badly enough to end his military career.  And while this has altered his career plans, and has been a disappointment to him, I can honestly say that I am glad he's out of that life.  I cant imagine the horror or stress of a war zone, but I do know that the horror and stress at home while someone you love is terrible.<br>
<br>
